          "id": 3,
          "title": "Part 3: Discussing a University Research Project",
          "description": "Two students, Emma and Tom, discuss their joint research project on urban foxes.",
          "audio": "audio/ViaTestPrep_Unique_1_Part3.mp3",
          "transcript": "<p><b>EMMA:</b> Hi Tom, have you had a chance to look at the data we collected for the urban fox project?</p><p><b>TOM:</b> I have, yeah. It's interesting how many sightings we got just from the industrial estate alone.</p><p><b>EMMA:</b> That surprised me too. I expected most of the activity to be in the residential gardens.</p><p><b>TOM:</b> Me too, honestly. I think it might be because there's less human activity at night in that industrial area, so the foxes feel safer there.</p><p><b>EMMA:</b> That makes sense. Should we focus the whole project on that one finding, or keep it broader?</p><p><b>TOM:</b> I'd lean towards keeping it broader, actually. If we only focus on the industrial estate, we might miss other interesting patterns in the residential data.</p><p><b>EMMA:</b> Fair point. What about our method, though? Do you think the camera traps gave us reliable data, or should we mention any limitations?</p><p><b>TOM:</b> I think we definitely need to mention limitations. The cameras only covered about 30% of the study area, so there's a good chance we missed some activity entirely.</p><p><b>EMMA:</b> Good point, I'll add that to the methodology section. Now, for the presentation itself, who's covering the introduction?</p><p><b>TOM:</b> I can do the introduction and the methodology, if you're happy to cover the results and discussion.</p><p><b>EMMA:</b> That works for me. How long do we have for the actual presentation?</p><p><b>TOM:</b> I checked with Doctor Ahmed, it's 15 minutes, plus 5 minutes for questions afterwards.</p><p><b>EMMA:</b> Okay, that's tighter than I thought. We'll need to practice the timing carefully.</p><p><b>TOM:</b> Definitely. Should we also include some of the photos from the camera traps in the slides?</p><p><b>EMMA:</b> Yes, I think that would really strengthen the presentation, visuals always help. Just the clearest two or three, though, not too many.</p><p><b>TOM:</b> Agreed. One last thing, when's the written report actually due?</p><p><b>EMMA:</b> The written report is due the same day as the presentation, the 20th of November.</p><p><b>TOM:</b> Right, we should start drafting that this week then, rather than leaving it all until the last minute.</p><p><b>EMMA:</b> Definitely agreed.</p>",
